{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503281","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503281"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:58:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:58:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2001"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2001","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2001"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.31,0.53,0.11,0.04,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2001"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83056"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2001","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2001"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2001"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68122"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"16"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1000"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"9586"},{"type":"tags","id":"12798"},{"type":"tags","id":"12803"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"786"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28420"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83056","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/83056"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA randomised controlled trial is conducted to trial a new drug in patients at risk of stroke. At the end of the study period, there were 20 strokes in the group of 100 patients who had received the active drug, compared to 25 strokes in the group of 100 patients who had received the placebo.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe control event rate is 25% and the treatment event rate is 20%.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the relative risk reduction for this treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["5%","20%","25%","50%","100%"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ERelative risk reduction (RRR) measures the proportional reduction in risk between treated and untreated groups. It is calculated by dividing the absolute risk reduction by the control group risk: RRR = (Control Event Rate - Treatment Event Rate) / Control Event Rate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe data can be arranged in a 2x2 table:\u003Cbr\u003E\u003Cdiv class=\u0022table-container\u0022\u003E\u003Ctable border=\u00271\u0027\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Cth\u003E\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth\u003EStroke\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth\u003ENo Stroke\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth\u003ETotal\u003C/th\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003ETreatment\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E20\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E80\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E100\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EControl\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E25\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E75\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E100\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003C/table\u003E\u003C/div\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E20%\u003C/strong\u003E is correct. In this case: RRR = (25% - 20%) / 25% = 5% / 25% = 0.20 = 20%. This means the treatment reduced the risk of stroke by 20% compared to placebo.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E5%\u003C/strong\u003E represents the absolute risk reduction (25% - 20% = 5%), not the relative risk reduction. While absolute risk reduction is often more clinically meaningful, it doesn\u0027t allow easy comparison between studies with different baseline risks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E25%\u003C/strong\u003E is the control group event rate (25 events per 100 patients = 25%). This is the baseline risk used in the RRR calculation but is not the RRR itself.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E50%\u003C/strong\u003E would represent a much larger treatment effect than was observed. This would mean the treatment halved the risk of stroke, which did not occur in this study.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E100%\u003C/strong\u003E would represent complete elimination of risk in the treatment group, which clearly did not occur as there were still 20 strokes in the treatment group.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile RRR is commonly used in medical literature to express treatment benefits, it can sometimes overstate the practical importance of a treatment effect, especially when baseline risks are low. This is why it\u0027s important to consider both relative and absolute measures of effect.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Relative risk reduction (RRR) is calculated by dividing the absolute risk reduction by the control event rate","RRR = (Control Event Rate - Treatment Event Rate) / Control Event Rate","RRR helps compare effectiveness across different studies but can overstate small absolute benefits"],"references":["British Medical Journal. \u2018How to calculate risk\u2019 in BMJ Best Practice, accessed 14/4/20, https://bestpractice.bmj.com/info/toolkit/learn-ebm/how-to-calculate-risk/."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68122"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2001"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68122","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/68122"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-01T21:45:31+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-01T21:47:01+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2001"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83056"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"16","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/16"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udcca","name":"Biostatistics","synonyms":null,"description":n